WEBVTT

00:04.115 --> 00:06.378
Did you like teaching? Oh, yes. Now that you're on 
the other side here. Very much so. I alluded to

00:15.132 --> 00:24.526
something about mass punishment earlier in our 
talk.

00:27.731 --> 00:31.557
The cadet wing Air Force Wing

00:33.578 --> 00:40.845
saw fit to campus all of its juniors at one time. 
What happened, somebody let the air out of all the

00:42.967 --> 00:46.591
seniors' tires. The seniors had a parking lot, 
they may still have, where only seniors could

00:46.691 --> 00:52.777
park. So somebody let the air out of their tires. 
And all the seniors got together and they camped

00:55.900 --> 00:58.642
with the juniors. Well, at that time, I was the 
senior instructor for Air Science 4, which are the

01:02.688 --> 01:09.358
seniors. And I had three, four other instructors 
who were also teaching Air Science 4. And I said,

01:17.890 --> 01:20.173
now, I'm getting ready to do something. I don't 
want you to criticize what I'm doing. I'm not

01:25.601 --> 01:27.223
asking that you do it. And if you're questioned by 
any of your students, just make some remark, well,

01:32.405 --> 01:37.372
I haven't even thought about that, or I haven't 
heard about it, or whatever you want to say. Just

01:37.672 --> 01:38.874
don't get in the act. So, first class, I walk in, and 
of course they come to attention. Good morning,

01:46.063 --> 01:47.285
gentlemen. This morning, before we take up the 
lesson for the day, we're going to have a standby

01:48.667 --> 01:53.954
inspection of uniform. I just went down the line 
and said, mister, I said, Isn't your tie tucked in

02:00.012 --> 02:02.594
at the wrong place? Doesn't it belong between the 
second and third button? Yes, sir. Okay, that's

02:07.538 --> 02:09.140
two diversions. Everybody in here says that's two 
diversions. Take a seat. I had three sections.

02:17.447 --> 02:19.268
Second section came along, same thing. Mister, 
don't you have on the wrong color sock? I've never

02:25.153 --> 02:28.356
seen that color sock with a uniform. Yes, sir. 
That's it. Non-rigged socks, that's two

02:30.522 --> 02:32.705
demerits, isn't it? Yes, sir. I said, everyone in 
the section is assessed two demerits. Take your

02:36.511 --> 02:38.494
seats. Third section came along, did the same 
thing. When the first section came back to class

02:41.518 --> 02:47.767
two days later, good morning, gentlemen. We're 
going to have a standby inspection again this

02:47.787 --> 02:50.812
morning. The wing commander was in that class. He 
said, sir, may I speak? I said, yes, sir. I said,

02:58.973 --> 03:04.540
Major, are you trying to tell us that mass 
punishment is wrong? I said, well, it didn't take

03:06.883 --> 03:09.126
you long to learn, did it? He said, well, for your 
information, we have released the juniors from

03:10.708 --> 03:16.455
their restriction to campus. I said, for your 
information, all those who are still on my desk may

03:17.937 --> 03:24.205
have gone to the Commandant's office. Get your ass 
out of here and go find out who let the air out of your

03:25.433 --> 03:31.519
tires and then punish them to the hilt. And it 
worked.

03:37.424 --> 03:42.729
Not only those three sections, but it spread 
through all the other sections. Well, I had some

03:42.749 --> 03:48.574
real interesting times.

03:48.594 --> 03:53.939
I was the sponsor of Squadron 7. Squadron 7 may not 
be what it used to be. But at that time, it was the top

03:58.168 --> 04:06.036
unit on the campus. I mean, scholastically, 
intramurally, it just took all of the trophies.

04:14.606 --> 04:17.148
And this was two years, the first two years I was 
there. And one day this Colonel John Way, who was a

04:19.050 --> 04:25.157
professor of air science, said, you know, when 
you're on top, It's easy to stay on top. I said, why

04:28.651 --> 04:31.155
don't you go get something that you don't have? I 
said, you name it, Colonel. What is it? He says,

04:35.721 --> 04:43.112
let's see you take the Houston military away from 
that infantry outfit. We'll do it. So I went down to

04:44.394 --> 04:47.959
squadron seven and called us cadet officers in. I 
said, you've got a challenge, because I'm going to

04:48.020 --> 04:52.086
give you the challenge. And I've got the challenge 
because the colonel put it on me. I said, we're

04:55.883 --> 04:58.487
going to win the Houston military. God, our outfit 
could never win that. Hell, it can't. And of

05:03.994 --> 05:11.424
course, the march-ins at football games are 
graded, and certain march-ins to the dining hall

05:03.994 --> 05:11.424
are graded. Everything military goes to the 
Houston military. Sure enough, Mother's Day,

05:16.732 --> 05:23.701
when it was announced, Squadron 7, Houston 
military. Well... That year I had a compassionate

05:24.942 --> 05:36.382
reassignment from A&M up to that Aviation 
Engineer Force because one of our children was

05:24.942 --> 05:36.382
sick and ultimately died.

05:38.826 --> 05:45.357
When Final Review came around, have you ever seen a 
Final Review before? When Final Review came

05:45.377 --> 05:48.402
around and First time they came around, you know, 
they saluted the commandant and all that

05:49.715 --> 05:53.159
business. And then they all went back out and got in 
the huddle, you know, and they put on their bars and

05:53.179 --> 06:01.650
everything, you know, and turned everything over 
to the juniors, and the juniors stepped up. They

06:01.670 --> 06:15.647
came walking across that field, and they handed me 
four sets of ropes, and it was all of them, the

06:01.670 --> 06:15.647
scholastic, the intramural,

06:01.670 --> 06:15.647
whatever the other one was, and then the Houston 
military. They said, here, Major. We know you

06:16.799 --> 06:20.525
can't wear them, but you can do something with 
them. And we had just built up a spree that, by

06:20.545 --> 06:32.744
golly, I stepped back, and they ran their outfit, 
and they came to me when they needed help, when they

06:20.545 --> 06:32.744
wanted something. And

06:32.764 --> 06:39.074
it was just one of the greatest things that had ever 
happened to me. A bunch of cadets were doing it.

06:43.942 --> 06:44.443
But... That old professor, he said, I never 
thought it would happen. I said, John, all you've

06:48.201 --> 06:52.627
got to do is just have a good bunch of cadets. He was 
from Oklahoma. I said, now you Hokies just don't

06:54.390 --> 06:59.917
understand. He died here last year.

07:04.223 --> 07:08.048
Were you sorry to leave AM99 after three years? Or 
were you ready for a transfer? Oh, I think we were

07:10.271 --> 07:11.393
ready. Our daughter contracted polio and an 
epidemic they had up there. She ultimately died of

07:19.940 --> 07:25.270
bronchial

07:19.940 --> 07:25.270
pneumonia. But I was ready to get moving

07:25.290 --> 07:31.542
and let's start.

07:40.870 --> 07:52.024
So your next assignment then was Director of 
Operations, Aviation, Engineering, Engineer

07:40.870 --> 07:52.024
Force, which you had from 1955 to 1956. Now, what 
were your functions there? And where was it

07:57.351 --> 08:02.037
first? Well, the Aviation Engineer Force was 
there at Walters, Mineral Wells. Oh, okay. Yeah.

08:08.965 --> 08:09.625
Which you talked about. Right. Yeah. And 
Navigation Engine Air Force is exactly what it

08:11.147 --> 08:14.891
said. It was, believe it or not, it was a bunch of 
Army troops that also had Air Force enlisted

08:14.991 --> 08:28.006
personnel and Air Force officers assigned to 
them. And they were under the control of the Air

08:28.026 --> 08:33.912
Force under a term called SCARWAW. Special 
Category Army with Air Force. And they were

08:39.438 --> 08:52.291
dedicated solely to construction of Air Force 
installations and bases and wherever the Air

08:39.438 --> 08:52.291
Force wanted them to go. And I had both operations 
and then at one time planned the program, which was

09:01.870 --> 09:25.971
worldwide assignment and utilization, war and 
peace, and figuring out how many battalions,

09:01.870 --> 09:25.971
regiments, brigades were needed in various parts 
of the country to support

09:01.870 --> 09:25.971
whatever the mission was and how many flying units 
we had.

09:28.280 --> 09:43.379
I guess one of the most interesting projects that 
we worked on, though, was I had an Army captain and

09:28.280 --> 09:43.379
an Air Force captain working for me, and we put 
together a manual that had never been assembled. I

09:43.439 --> 09:57.477
mean, you could go here and get this and here and get 
that, but we assembled a manual that could

09:43.439 --> 09:57.477
actually be carried onto a job, and it was recovery 
of an Air Force installation following nuclear

09:43.439 --> 09:57.477
attack. so that they didn't have to carry a library 
as big as that over there. They just carried one

10:04.043 --> 10:07.168
manual, and the whole thing was there. And it took 
us about six months to put the thing together, and

10:07.188 --> 10:13.758
it was ultimately published. And even though they 
abolished SCARWOF, and all those Army troops went

10:13.778 --> 10:26.316
back to the Army, and our Air Force went back into 
our own engineering units, base maintenance

10:13.778 --> 10:26.316
units, We still buy copies of the manual around.

10:32.948 --> 10:38.453
Of course, this was a period when the atomic bomb 
and, well, when we were building up our atomic

10:32.948 --> 10:38.453
arsenal. Was there a lot of interest within the Air 
Force at this time?

10:50.566 --> 10:51.287
Oh, yeah, very definitely. I used to kid my 
contemporaries that If I went over to the Planning

10:57.734 --> 11:11.469
and Programming Office, over on one corner of the 
desk, I had worldwide utilization of aviation

10:57.734 --> 11:11.469
engineer forces, and then over on this, return of 
SCARWAC units to the Army. If a breeze came along

11:12.370 --> 11:24.703
and mixed these papers, you know, well, that was 
the biggest job we had for months, because here we

11:12.370 --> 11:24.703
were planning how to use these guys for years in a 
war and peace, and over here, I'll give them back to

11:25.308 --> 11:27.471
the Army within 30 days. But you go through that 
quite often. Of course, this is a time when the Air

11:33.220 --> 11:43.837
Force is enlarging, and we're getting now into 
strategic air command. Were you building a lot of

11:44.558 --> 11:52.370
air bases at this time? Yeah. because of the 
agreements with the labor and so on, these units

11:54.333 --> 12:22.247
would stay in a training status most of the time, 
but could be used downrange, down the Bahamas, in

11:54.333 --> 12:22.247
Iceland, and we could use them in the Pacific, but 
not in the Connus in the continental United States

12:22.818 --> 12:33.294
because that was to be left open for bidding on the 
economy. What were the major bases that you built?

12:37.120 --> 12:47.897
Well, no base per se, but additional facilities at 
Thule, for instance, at Hickam itself. So you were

12:49.598 --> 12:52.602
back in the construction field. Yeah. And at 
Tachikawa in Japan, at Clark.

13:03.217 --> 13:11.989
Did you have any dealings with any of the building 
that was going on in the new line, any of the

13:03.217 --> 13:11.989
Canadian strategic defenses at that time? No, I 
didn't at that time. I did later on, but not at that

13:13.631 --> 13:16.635
time. of course this is a time with the enlargement 
of the strategic air command did you have any

13:18.758 --> 13:41.577
dealings with any construction as far as they were 
concerned no see most of theirs were caught us and

13:18.758 --> 13:41.577
they'd be under contract under contract okay and 
of course this is the 50s was an era when general

