And about half those eyes look at me like, what's 
Zucker going to

17:04.309 --> 17:15.319
do? He was exactly what was needed at the time.

17:23.226 --> 17:27.891
Capable individual.

17:27.911 --> 17:30.233
Not afraid to speak out. I'm sure that

17:31.748 --> 17:43.121
we bought time with a lot of his boldness, his 
bluff, and that we needed. Was there a friction

17:44.622 --> 17:48.847
between the Strategic Air Command and other parts 
of the Air Force? Always is. Why? Well, you trace as

17:53.492 --> 18:00.760
a rule who would go to the top. to run the Air Force, 
you'd always find that they came out of the

18:02.393 --> 18:07.541
strategic command. Strategic air command would 
graduate to the top.

18:14.151 --> 18:22.944
And training command and tactical air command did 
never make it up. They'd make it so high, but they'd

18:22.964 --> 18:25.047
never get to the top. And so that's most of it.

18:32.650 --> 18:45.772
That is not really where most of the

18:32.650 --> 18:45.772
animosity

18:32.650 --> 18:45.772
and friction really is. There are other places 
that have friction.

18:54.025 --> 18:56.970
In our business,

18:58.098 --> 19:02.022
And it didn't bother me, because I wore a blue suit. 
But

19:02.102 --> 19:21.982
remember I said earlier that at West Point, when 
you graduated, and they rank the class, and then

19:02.102 --> 19:21.982
everybody gets to pick what branch they want to go 
into.

19:23.303 --> 19:27.227
The top of the class usually picks the Corps of 
Engineers. It's a good honorable profession and

19:28.507 --> 19:35.314
it provides you something to do after you leave the 
service. It's a damn good service to be in. And then

19:41.321 --> 19:42.782
they go on down the line. And the bottom is the 
infantry.

19:49.069 --> 19:54.995
Well, years ago this happened and still does. And 
so before the Air Force had its own academy, before

19:57.869 --> 20:15.489
the Air Force started building its own system, 
this guy would say, I'm going to aviation cadets

19:57.869 --> 20:15.489
before I go to the infantry.

20:15.509 --> 20:26.661
OK, now you've got a guy that's down here in the 
bottom quarter of the class that went to aviation

20:15.509 --> 20:26.661
cadets

20:15.509 --> 20:26.661
instead of going to the infantry. which he would 
have had to done, because there was none of this

20:27.485 --> 20:32.330
other choice assignments left. He comes out of 
aviation cadets, and all these guys go along for 25

20:34.972 --> 20:55.652
years, and now here you got, at the top of the Air 
Force, a guy that was in the bottom quarter of the

20:34.972 --> 20:55.652
class, and you got this engineer group sitting 
over here that was at the top of the class, and

20:34.972 --> 20:55.652
they're just like that.

20:57.978 --> 21:07.769
Now, it's getting better as we get our own people 
out of the Air Force Academy. Because we're not

21:07.789 --> 21:19.001
getting as many of this bottom quarter coming out 
of West Point or coming out of Annapolis or Point.

21:19.021 --> 21:21.404
Let me tell you, it was rough. I mean, again, not me, 
because I'm wearing blue. But you go in to brief one

21:25.128 --> 21:27.951
of these commanders and tell him, The core, don't 
tell me about the core. Just, you know, turn

21:33.904 --> 21:35.346
themselves off. I don't believe it. You go back 
over there and you tell that core, you know.

21:40.633 --> 21:43.437
There's just a lot of animosity in between. And, 
you know, you can expect it. It's built in. I mean,

21:46.320 --> 21:47.622
it's there. Anytime you've got the rank and file 
system,

21:48.223 --> 21:55.913
and they can carry it for years.

