26:41.383 --> 26:54.161
maintained as to how much pressure we put on the 
contractors to deliver what was right and so on.

26:54.181 --> 27:07.780
And we ended up, even though I was not there when it 
was completed, I hadn't been moved to Africa by

26:54.181 --> 27:07.780
then, but a very, very minimum of claims from the 
contractor. At that time, I worked for an Army

27:08.182 --> 27:10.826
colonel. So I was, again, mixed into this joint 
service thing. And I truthfully must say, just by

27:17.676 --> 27:36.585
having lived the Corps life and being able to 
adjust to just about anything, I don't care

27:17.676 --> 27:36.585
whether the guy's Army, Navy, or what. what the guy 
produces, how he treats people.

27:44.836 --> 27:46.718
Anyway, we got along fine. At this time, of course, 
France was still in NATO, and they pulled out a few

27:48.119 --> 27:53.405
years after that. How are the relations with the 
French army, or the French officers? Great.

27:59.691 --> 28:00.032
Great? Still great? Yeah. In 56 and 57? Yep. 
Terrific. Yeah, the fact is, you see, on that whole

28:07.362 --> 28:19.137
tour, I felt this because,

28:07.362 --> 28:19.137
like you say, how it was in relation then. Then when 
I left there and went down to North Africa for a

28:19.618 --> 28:32.695
short period of time and I went to England, that's 
where I really felt it because when we pulled out of

28:19.618 --> 28:32.695
England, I mean pulled out of France, we brought 
them to England, you see. Because there we brought

28:33.080 --> 28:38.588
the units that we pulled out of France. We brought 
