29:44.727 --> 29:48.552
they were both American and French. Oh. Yeah. And 
so how would it work? The Air Force would say, okay,

29:52.898 --> 30:05.218
we want you to go build this landing strip or 
something like that, or go build a building on this

29:52.898 --> 30:05.218
base, and then you'd sit down and draw the plans? 
No, we did not design it. All we did was just

30:06.800 --> 30:09.024
supervise the construction. Oh, okay. The plans 
came to us from our own organization in Paris.

30:15.093 --> 30:15.614
Okay. That was the joint construction they were 
headed by. Well, it would alternate. One term it

30:20.727 --> 30:25.232
would be an Army guy, the next term it would be a 
Navy, and the next term it would be an Air Force. And

30:25.252 --> 30:28.115
then it would just keep rotating. And it was called 
the Joint Construction Agency. Everybody in

30:31.719 --> 30:34.462
there was just a mixture. Is this Joint 
Construction Agency? Is that a fairly new output?

30:40.148 --> 30:42.270
No, it's no longer in existence. It's no longer OK. 
Yeah. Tell me a little bit about that. I mean, when

30:46.515 --> 30:48.297
did they start this agency? I've never seen it. OK. 
Let's

30:50.660 --> 30:55.064
see. We went over and they started just for the 
task. Why do they have this agency? They started

31:02.632 --> 31:12.002
just for the task of building bases?

31:12.022 --> 31:12.362
Let's see. We went over. It must

31:14.573 --> 31:25.230
have started about 51 or 52. And when we left there 
to go down to Africa, it was phasing down then. And

31:35.446 --> 31:40.294
the only reason they pulled me out early is the 
officer that I had worked for at the Aviation and

31:41.759 --> 31:48.107
Air Force asked for me in Africa. He was down there. 
And he asked, he says, since you're phasing down,

31:49.068 --> 31:54.976
can you send Johnson to me now? He'd been trying for 
a year to get me down here. And so they finally said,

31:57.860 --> 31:59.762
yeah, we'll let him go. Now, why did they even have 
this agency, the Joint Construction Agency? Just

32:05.229 --> 32:09.555
to explain, why did they even institute it?

32:11.898 --> 32:41.230
I can't

32:11.898 --> 32:41.230
answer the question

32:11.898 --> 32:41.230
with 100% assurance that I'm right, because

32:11.898 --> 32:41.230
there was so much demand for construction 
throughout, I have to remember where all it was

32:11.898 --> 32:41.230
now, in Italy. in Greece, Spain, in Germany, in 
France, that somebody made the decision that it

32:41.783 --> 33:07.588
was bigger than the Corps of Engineers could 
handle on its own, and that the Navy ought to have a

32:41.783 --> 33:07.588
voice in it, and the Air Force ought to have a voice 
in it, especially when it affected their own civil

33:07.771 --> 33:11.335
combat agency. So they formed this thing. Now, 
when it fell apart at the time I went to Africa, then

33:13.258 --> 33:32.342
it went back to Army everywhere in Europe except 
England, and that belongs to the Air Force, and the

33:13.258 --> 33:32.342
Navy in Spain. And the Army has all the rest of it, 
even now. So the building then, they had

33:38.348 --> 33:45.278
accomplished the mission of that building in 
those six or seven years that it was in existence.

33:45.299 --> 33:50.406
And then they decided to phase it out, and the Corps 
could handle whatever building was necessary.

33:51.067 --> 33:52.249
OK. All right. So you went to Libya in 1957 as

33:52.870 --> 33:59.119
the director engineer. And construction, 
engineering and construction. I had 36 people

34:02.665 --> 34:05.569
working for me there. And we had. Did they give you a 
promotion or not? No, I was still a major. I made

34:10.321 --> 34:13.745
Lieutenant Colonel while there.

34:15.507 --> 34:21.896
We had Morocco, Libya, Italy, Greece, and Turkey. 
That's where our units were scattered, in those

34:23.358 --> 34:28.524
five countries.

34:31.629 --> 34:32.970
Well, it wasn't too bad. We had one base in Italy. We 
had one base in Greece, we had two in Morocco, we had

34:36.753 --> 34:52.113
one in Libya, but we had about five or six in Turkey 
and Crete.

34:52.133 --> 34:54.416
A good bit of traveling then. So did you travel 
around from base to base doing any, you know,

34:54.516 --> 35:02.146
anytime they needed some construction?

35:04.530 --> 35:04.850
Yeah. Were there major operations? We

35:07.516 --> 35:13.503
handled two different types of operations. At 
that time, a

35:13.523 --> 35:27.821
minor construction project was something that 
ran from $25,000 to $100,000. And that we could

35:28.002 --> 35:37.253
design, and if the command had the money, commit 
the money and go. If it was major construction, it

35:37.773 --> 35:44.420
had to go before the Congress for congressional 
approval and appropriation. We would work with

35:46.341 --> 35:54.289
the programmers to define it, and the programmers 
would put it on the documents and get it on up the

35:46.341 --> 35:54.289
line and then get it approved. Once it was 
approved, then we would work with the Corps of

35:54.550 --> 36:03.038
Engineers to see that they designed what we 
intended to have built. and they'd take over and

36:03.524 --> 36:13.522
finish the design, let the contract, supervise 
the contract, and then we would run the acceptance

36:03.524 --> 36:13.522
inspection and so on. So it's kind of a split 
operation. It's part of what the magnitude was.

36:21.557 --> 36:27.287
Like a big hangar at Tripoli, Libya, Wheeler. All 
that we did was define the project and say, this is

36:28.094 --> 36:35.382
what we want, and then look over the core shoulder 
and say, OK, we agree with the design. Build it. And

36:36.643 --> 36:38.885
then they'd build it. Did Mrs. Johnson get to go 
with you to Libya? Yes, and both boys. We have two

36:44.071 --> 36:45.873
boys. So she was in France with you and in Libya, and 
then in the United Kingdom? Yeah. Oh, good. So what

36:52.940 --> 36:55.603
were the conditions like in Libya? Well, when we 
were there they were great because we moved right

36:56.545 --> 37:07.037
into the first place we lived was a brand new 
masonry house. So new that it hadn't even seasoned

37:08.639 --> 37:19.431
and you could be sitting like we are here talking 
and least little rise in temperature and

37:08.639 --> 37:19.431
something would go. And a seed would pop out of a 
little plaster. They hadn't used clean sand, and

37:23.461 --> 37:27.205
it was a grass seed, you know. We'd be talking some 
more, and something would go... And another one

37:28.026 --> 37:33.212
would pop out up there. But all in all, they were 
good. And we moved from there to another, what they

37:34.874 --> 37:39.919
call, villa. And then, ultimately, we moved on 
base in the base quarters.

37:46.887 --> 37:47.848
We had... I'd say an above average houseboy. The 
women don't work down there. The men work. You can

37:54.990 --> 37:59.276
do the domestic work. We found it pretty 
interesting.

38:03.541 --> 38:12.513
It gave my older boy, or our older boy, a challenge 
in life and an outlook that has led to his

38:03.541 --> 38:12.513
profession. He is a graduate of American 
University.

38:19.823 --> 38:26.049
International Relations and his postgraduate 
master's degree from the University of Utah. He is

38:26.769 --> 38:29.472
a Persian expert. He speaks Arabic, Fazi, French, 
as well as English. He happens to be a major in the

38:34.416 --> 38:38.300
Air Force. That is interesting. And this is where 
he picked up that interest. That first challenge.

38:45.866 --> 38:49.830
Well, why did you only stay there for about a year 
and then go to the United Kingdom in 1959? The tour

38:50.587 --> 38:56.515
in Libya is what they call a short tour. And I 
offered them a short extension in Libya or a long

38:57.296 --> 39:09.734
extension in the United Kingdom. And the 
personnel people and the civil engineer people

39:09.754 --> 39:15.522
got to wrestling. And they said, well, under the 
conditions, what's happening in the United

39:15.542 --> 39:20.509
Kingdom? let's move into the United Kingdom. And 
what was happening that they needed to? That's

39:26.064 --> 39:34.536
when these units in France were being programmed 
into England and into Germany. Okay, let's talk

39:34.556 --> 39:35.777
about this. I've heard some interesting comments 
about when we moved out of France. Okay, the

39:45.210 --> 39:49.416
project of the move of Air Force units from France 
to England was called Red Richard. That was the

39:55.373 --> 39:56.254
code word. It was an unclassified code word. But 
anything that was Red Richard, everybody knew

39:58.638 --> 40:10.777
money-wise, program-wise, that was to get a unit 
or had to do with moving from France to the United

39:58.638 --> 40:10.777
Kingdom. And I

40:10.797 --> 40:15.825
was titled Director of Project Management. I had 
master planning, planning, programming, and

40:19.117 --> 40:44.462
fiscal control under me in the United Kingdom in 
civil engineering, which put me right in sitting

40:19.117 --> 40:44.462
with the commanders and the engineers and the 
general from headquarters Air Force Europe that

40:44.965 --> 40:52.532
with the units moving out as to what they needed and 
what had to be done to the bases that, you know, that

40:44.965 --> 40:52.532
they were designated to go to and so on. What we had 
to do with emergency money, which is, you know, the

40:53.393 --> 41:02.100
money that we had right now that we could use, what 
we had to go back to Congress to get approval on and

40:53.393 --> 41:02.100
so on. But the project was called Red Richard. And 
it was just one of those all-night, all-day

41:04.843 --> 41:11.549
things. You get it done and... What were the 
feelings toward the French in your command at this

41:13.838 --> 41:18.102
time?

41:21.105 --> 41:29.873
Well, I think the feeling in our command,

41:21.105 --> 41:29.873
being on the continent, those units weren't in our 
command. They were in the 16th Air Force, I guess it

41:29.933 --> 41:35.959
was. And everybody in the United Kingdom was in the 
3rd Air Force. Well, they weren't our units until

41:39.082 --> 41:42.765
they moved to us. You know, in the United Kingdom, 
it was kind of nice a lot. But the overall feeling

41:47.635 --> 41:54.385
was that, you know, the French have really slipped 
through, after all. For years, we've been pouring

41:54.405 --> 41:56.287
money into there. And for years, they've been part 
of the program. And now, this has happened.

42:04.699 --> 42:10.086
But even now, today, in 81, you know, they're not 
completely out of it. No. You know? It's a crazy

42:11.416 --> 42:23.832
agreement or arrangement, but

42:11.416 --> 42:23.832
it's been harmful to the total force, but we've 
lived with it. I've heard some comments from other

42:23.853 --> 42:40.815
generals saying that when the American forces 
moved out of France and moved everything, even the

42:23.853 --> 42:40.815
telephones and everything that they could, it was 
at the... Was that the order that came down from

42:41.572 --> 42:43.374
Tom? Well... Or was that just resentment?

42:52.084 --> 42:52.204
No. I wouldn't say it was resentment. I'd say that 
was, you know, move whatever you can. You know,

42:56.850 --> 43:02.456
you've got to make this move with the least amount 
of additional expenditure. At Chambord, when we

43:03.518 --> 43:09.925
first got to France as a resident engineer and Our 
first quarters were on Showmont. Later we moved

43:11.849 --> 43:14.513
over near the other base.

43:16.356 --> 43:31.476
That weekend or the very next weekend, they 
dedicated a Statue of Liberty that bronze or brass

43:16.356 --> 43:31.476
was about that tall, standing on a pedestal that 
was again about that tall. And that thing had been

43:31.496 --> 43:39.287
built from the pattern that the statue is made in 
the New York Harbor. But when that unit moved from

43:40.212 --> 43:48.620
Showmont to Lake and Heath, they even took the 
Statue of Liberty with them. Vive la France, and

43:50.562 --> 43:53.425
we're back to help in all this business. And then 
two years later, you can stay, but your nukes have

43:53.505 --> 43:57.509
got to go. Well, what does a nuclear force do?

44:04.436 --> 44:08.380
Where did you store the nuclear weapons that 
America had in France? Yeah, did we store them back

44:09.052 --> 44:12.637
in Great Britain? Oh, yeah. Yeah, we've got 
terrific storage facilities in Britain. And did

44:18.525 --> 44:19.947
you help construct those? Oh, yeah. Some of the 
units, though, now went to Germany. All of them did

44:24.253 --> 44:25.895
not go to England. We picked up there were, in 
France, there was nuclear

44:25.915 --> 44:36.109
either three or four wings. We got two of them in and 
Germany got through them. The rest were

44:40.549 --> 44:44.394
transported out. The pressure wasn't on on them. 
They ultimately moved them out also. The pressure

44:48.359 --> 44:54.107
was to maintain the nuclear force in Europe.

44:59.194 --> 45:06.244
Was there special problems with building sites 
where you could store nuclear weapons? No. But we

45:08.030 --> 45:10.654
already had them. We already had nuclear weapons 
in England. And so you just, you didn't have to

45:13.698 --> 45:16.943
expand them, they were large enough? No, they had 
to be expanded.

45:22.250 --> 45:34.628
Bases were, like we had a combination of

45:22.250 --> 45:34.628
Bentwater's Woodbridge, two bases about six 
miles apart, that one wing had. It had two

45:36.033 --> 45:38.896
squadrons on one location and one on the other. We 
put another squadron in there that belonged to one

45:39.537 --> 45:42.961
of these outfits coming in. So you build up a little 
more facility. But fortunately in England, where

45:48.206 --> 46:03.923
we have ammo and nuke storage, the British had 
pretty good foresight and put sufficient

45:48.206 --> 46:03.923
clearance around them.

46:09.758 --> 46:15.987
So was that your major task when you were in England 
for those two years, 1959 and 1960? Yeah, I guess it

46:17.730 --> 46:21.115
was for that period.

46:29.086 --> 46:36.357
Two

46:29.086 --> 46:36.357
interesting things happened then. You asked 
earlier, way back there before A&M, I happened to

46:37.923 --> 46:49.916
be the district commissioner of the Mayflower 
District of the Boy Scouts of America. And that was

46:49.956 --> 46:54.761
just made up of Boy Scout units in the United 
Kingdom. So that was a freebie job, a service job.

46:59.426 --> 47:06.073
And the man that I worked for in England during that 
time period was the first one that my own

47:06.678 --> 47:09.617
effectiveness report ever since.

